comments.text:
You know, eating insects instead of meat or unsustainable fish is so 
healthy and beneficial to the environment that FAO, the Food and 
Agricultural Organization of the UN, recommends it. They're a perfectly 
normal everyday food in large parts of the world and seeing them as 
disgusting non-food is primarily a western thing.

The kinds of insect food that's primarily sold in the western countries now 
is mostly things like cricket flour and protein bars. You don't have to eat 
insects whole if you find that too disgusting, at least until you've gotten 
used to them.

Well, they have actually eaten bugs before. Just not intentionally. It's 
impossible to produce some/all plant foods without some insect fragments 
getting into the product. There are actually rules stating the maximum 
amount of insect fragments allowed in, for instance, chocolate or flour.

I've intentionally eaten mealworms and crickets and I really liked the 
taste of the crickets (mild taste, similar to nuts or popcorn, crispy 
texture). The mealworms were crispy thanks to the way I cooked them but 
they were rather tasteless because I didn't use any spices.﻿
